### 29.

1\. Now at that time a certain Bhikkhu entered the village for alms
without a girdle on, and in the highway <span
id="fr_378"></span>[1](#fn_371.md) his waist-cloth fell down <span
id="fr_379"></span>[2](#fn_372.md). The people made an outcry, and that
Bhikkhu was abashed.

On his return to the Ârâma, that Bhikkhu told this matter to the
Bhikkhus, and the Bhikkhus told it to the Blessed One.

'You are not, O Bhikkhus, to enter the village without a girdle on.
Whosoever does so, shall be guilty of a dukka*t*a. I allow, O Bhikkhus,
a girdle <span id="fr_380"></span>[3](#fn_373.md).'

2\. Now at that time the *Kh*abbaggiya Bhikkhus wore (&c., as usual,
ending with)

'You are not, O Bhikkhus, to wear special girdles <span
id="fr_381"></span>[4](#fn_374.md)--those made of many strings plaited

<span id="page_143">p. 143</span>

together <span id="fr_382"></span>[1](#fn_375.md), those made like the head
of a water-snake <span id="fr_383"></span>[2](#fn_376.md), girdles with
tambourines on them <span id="fr_384"></span>[3](#fn_377.md), girdles with
beads on (or with ornaments hanging from them) <span
id="fr_385"></span>[4](#fn_378.md). Whosoever does so, shall be guilty of a
dukka*t*a. I allow you, O Bhikkhus, girdles of two kinds--those made of
strips of cloth, and those . . . . <span
id="fr_386"></span>[5](#fn_379.md)'

The borders of the girdles decayed through age.

'I allow, O Bhikkhus, an edging of brighter material <span
id="fr_387"></span>[6](#fn_380.md) and strengthening at the ends <span
id="fr_388"></span>[7](#fn_381.md).'

The end of the girdle where the knot was tied decayed through age <span
id="fr_389"></span>[8](#fn_382.md).

'I allow, O Bhikkhus, a buckle <span id="fr_390"></span>[9](#fn_383.md).'

\[A paragraph on the substances of which it may be made, as usual, see
Mahâvagga VI, 12, 3; *K*ullavagga V, 5, 2, &c.,

<span id="page_144">p. 144</span>

adding at the end 'and made of string.'\]

3\. Now at the time the venerable Ânanda went into the village for alms
with light garments on <span id="fr_391"></span>[1](#fn_384.md) and his
garments were blown up by a whirlwind.

The venerable Ânanda, on returning to the Ârâma, told this matter to the
Bhikkhus; and the Bhikkhus told this matter to the Blessed One.

'I allow, O Bhikkhus, a block <span id="fr_392"></span>[2](#fn_385.md) (to
be used as a weight) or a chain <span id="fr_393"></span>[3](#fn_386.md).'

\[Similar paragraph to that just above as to the substances of which the
block may be made.\]

Now at that time the Bhikkhus fastened the block or the chain
immediately on to their robes; and the robes gave way.

They told this matter to the Blessed One.

'I allow, O Bhikkhus, a piece of phalaka cloth <span
id="fr_394"></span>[4](#fn_387.md)to attach the block or the chain to.'

They fastened the phalaka cloth for the block or the chain on to the
edge of the robe; and the corner came open <span
id="fr_395"></span>[5](#fn_388.md).

<span id="page_145">p. 145</span>

They told this matter to the Blessed One.

'I allow you, O Bhikkhus, to fasten the phalaka cloth for the block on
the edge of the robe, and to fasten the phalaka cloth for the chain
seven or eight finger-breadths up the robe.'

4\. Now at that time the *Kh*abbaggiya Bhikkhus wore (&c., as usual,
ending with)

'You are not, O Bhikkhus, to wear your under garments arranged as laymen
do, nor arranged with appendages like elephant-trunks <span
id="fr_396"></span>[1](#fn_389.md), nor arranged like fishing-nets <span
id="fr_397"></span>[2](#fn_390.md), nor arranged with four corners
showing <span id="fr_398"></span>[3](#fn_391.md), nor arranged like
flower-stands <span id="fr_399"></span>[4](#fn_392.md), nor arranged like
rows of jewelry <span id="fr_400"></span>[5](#fn_393.md). Whosoever does
so, shall be guilty of a dukka*t*a.

\[Similar paragraph, ending\]

'You are not, O Bhikkhus, to wear your upper <span
id="fr_401"></span>[6](#fn_394.md)

<span id="page_146">p. 146</span>

garments as the laymen do. Whosoever does so, shall be guilty of a
dukka*t*a.'

5\. \[Similar paragraph, ending\]

'You are not, O Bhikkhus, to wear your under garments <span
id="fr_402"></span>[1](#fn_395.md) as the king's porters do <span
id="fr_403"></span>[1](#fn_395.md). Whosoever does so, shall be guilty of a
dukka*t*a.'

