### Footnotes

<span id="fn_371"></span>[142:1](sbe20044.htm#fr_378.md) Rathiyâya. The Old
Commentary on the Bhikkhunî., vibhaṅga, Pâ*k*ittiya XIV, says, Rathiyâ
ti ra*kkh*â. The word recurs, ibid., Pâ*k*ittiya LXXXVI, XCVI (the last
of which is nearly the same as our passage here). For the more usual
form rathikâ, see *K*ullavagga X, 12.

<span id="fn_372"></span>[142:2](sbe20044.htm#fr_379.md) Pabhassittha.
Compare Sutta-vibhaṅga, Pâ*k*ittiya LXXXIII, 1, 2. It is from the root
bhrams, not bhâs.

<span id="fn_373"></span>[142:3](sbe20044.htm#fr_380.md) The use of this
has already been enjoined at Mahâvagga I, 25, 9, 10. It was to be tied
on round the waist, over the waist-cloth, to keep it in its place.

<span id="fn_374"></span>[142:4](sbe20044.htm#fr_381.md) It is curious that
ka*t*i-suttaka*m*, a kind of girdle which would seem properly to belong
here, has been included in a former list of forbidden articles at V, 2,
I.

<span id="fn_375"></span>[143:1](sbe20044.htm#fr_382.md) Kalâbuka*m*. See
Buddhaghosa's note at p. 3'9 of the text, and compare Böhtlingk-Roth
under kalâpa, kalâpaka.

<span id="fn_376"></span>[143:2](sbe20044.htm#fr_383.md) De*dd*ubhaka*m*
nâma udaka-sappi-sîsa-sadisa*m* (B.). De*dd*ubha corresponds to the
later Sanskrit du*nd*ubha, an older form of which is dundubha.

<span id="fn_377"></span>[143:3](sbe20044.htm#fr_384.md) Mura*g*a,
literally, 'tambourines;' but see Buddhaghosa's note, loc. cit.

<span id="fn_378"></span>[143:4](sbe20044.htm#fr_385.md) Maddavîna*m* nâma
pâmaṅga-sa*nth*âna*m* (B.). On pâmaṅga, see our note at *K*ullavagga V,
2, I.

<span id="fn_379"></span>[143:5](sbe20044.htm#fr_386.md) Sûkarantaka*m*.
See Buddhaghosa's note at p. 319 of the text. We do not venture to
translate the term.

<span id="fn_380"></span>[143:6](sbe20044.htm#fr_387.md) Sobha*n*am nâma
ve*tth*etvâ mukha-va*tt*i-sibhana*m* (B.). In the Ma*ggh*ima Sîla, § 3,
sobha*n*akam or sobh.ana-kara*n*am (so Rh. D.'s MS.) is a kind of game
or show.

<span id="fn_381"></span>[143:7](sbe20044.htm#fr_388.md) Gu*n*aka*m* nâma
mudika(?muddhika)-san*th*ânena sibbana*m* (B.). Clough, under gu*n*a,
